Project level outcomes are i) improving access to capital, and ii) supporting value creation for investees. The
main market-creation outcome is increased market competitiveness through demonstration of confidence in
the Fund Manager sending a signal for other fund managers to enter the country.&nbsp;

(i) Stakeholder: by adding 34MW of capacity to the grid, the Project contributes to meeting demand growth in the Libreville area as well as improving reliability of supply. As per the utility company Socit d'<c3>?nergie et d'Eau du Gabon ("SEEG"), the peak electricity demand of c. 277MW in 2019 in the Libreville area exceeds the available generating capacity of c. 239MW resulting in a supply-demand gap. Through provision of low-cost baseload capacity, the Project also contributes to reducing the cost of service; 

(ii) Environmental: The Project will generate energy from an efficient, renewable source, and thus reduce the country's GHG emissions. It also contributes to reducing the importance of thermal capacity in the generation mix, which stood at c. 68% of the capacity as of end 2019.

 (iii) Competitiveness: The successful implementation of the Project, as the country's first project-financed IPP, will have important demonstration effects.

1.	Increased access to finance for MEs: IFC anticipates that the Project will increase access to finance for MFIs and MEs, with a focus on women entrepreneurs and micro-housing finance;
2.	Market creation: The Project is expected to increase the inclusiveness of microfinance through demonstrating that there is a business case for implementing new products that could expand their reach to currently underserved market segments, and that they can be commercially viable, despite the perception of high risk;
3.	Incisiveness via gender finance: IFC anticipates that the Project will increase access to finance for women entrepreneurs who own and/or manage micro enterprises, with 50% of IFC's proceeds earmarked for these purposes;
4.	Inclusiveness via micro-housing finance: IFC anticipates that the Project will sustain affordable housing finance for the low-income segment, mostly in rural areas.

The most significant expected development impact resulting from the project  involves:
i)	Increased financing of Sustainable Energy Projects in the country, including Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy projects, thus supporting Romania's efforts to achieve the EU Climate and Energy Targets;
ii)	Supporting access to finance for SMEs in the country; 
iii)	Increased access to finance for mortgage borrowers in the country, helping reduce the substantial mortgage finance gap between Romania and average EU levels;
Promoting the development and integration of capital markets in Romania by supporting the first RON-denominated B3T2  on the Romanian market. A successful issuance and subsequent listing on the Bucharest Stock Exchange is expected to result in further B3T2 bond issuances by other Romanian banks in the nearby future and widening of the investor base.

(i) access to growth capital for Fund investees as well as providing knowledge and skills through complementary advisory engagements, which is expected to close a significant private equity gap in these markets and build the capacity of the SME investees; 
(ii) the growth of the Fund's investee companies is expected to result in job creation and economic growth; and 
(iii) contribute to market creation by enabling private sector development through demonstrating the viability of investing into SMEs in countries largely underserved by PE funds.

The expected development impact of the Fund includes (i) improved access to long-term, patient, risk capital
for fund investees which should lead to (ii) accelerated investee growth delivered via a deliberated approach
from the General Partner through collaborating with management teams and providing hands-on financial,
operations, strategic and governance guidance; (iii) increased PE investment levels are expected to improve
market competitiveness by small and mid-cap companies supported by good PE investors and (iv) expanded
access to institutional capital in Vietnam anticipated from new institutional and private investors.&nbsp;

i) Stakeholder impacts: to improve SMEs' access to green financing/leasing, and to increase affordability of green leasing products; 
ii) Environmental and social impact: to generate sizable green electricity and to reduce green-house gas emission;
iii) Market standard setting: to promote broader adoption of internationally acceptable green financing principals/standards; 
iv) Market demonstration effect: to introduce the first sizable public green financing issued by a SME-focused private sector leasing company in China.


 
