 access and quality of civil aviation services; 
 (b) Economy-wide
 impact: increase in GDP, employment and government revenues; 
 (c) Contribution
 to market creation as the first large-scale PPP project in the country; 
 (d) Integration:
 as Serbia's largest and busiest international airport, Belgrade Airport will
 handle all the potential growth in international traffic and contribute to
 opening access to new short and long-haul markets.

(i) Increase Access to Finance in Low Tier Regions: The proposed investment is expected to support big-data based micro lending to efficiently tap underserved MSMEs in lower tier segments; 
(ii) Promote market integration by supporting the development of new product for MSMEs: who are small business owners of mom-and-pop shops/kiosk or tech fans, to help distribute Xiaomi's product in low tier cities to promote market integration between urban and rural area; and 
(iii) Cross-Border Expansion: With the demonstration in China, the knowledge will be replicated to the countries where Xiaomi smartphone already has footprint.

(i) Increasing competitiveness by support regional SME champion with active consolidation strategy;
(ii) Significant market creation effect through the issuance of the first bond of this type in Romania, helping set the standards for future issuances;
(iii) Increased access to finance for local SMEs, especially operating in less developed regions of the country.

1.	Increased access to finance for SMEs - The Project aims to increase access to finance for SMEs to augment economic activity, create job opportunities, and contribute to economic development in the country;
2.	Increased funding for climate-smart projects -The Project will provide long-term financing for climate-smart and environmentally friendly projects contributing to Thailand's commitment to increase sustainable energy resources and decrease greenhouse gas emissions;
3.	Market creation - The green tranche of the bond will the first bond issuance aligned with the Global Bond Principles in Thailand, which will result in creation of a new asset class in the country and hence, is anticipated to support the country to meet its climate-smart investment targets and financing gap required to address climate change challenges.

- Access to Quality Pharmaceutical Products: The Project is expected to increase availability of quality pharmaceutical products in the region and combat the prevalence of counterfeit and fake drugs.<c2>&nbsp;
- Increase Affordability of Pharmaceutical Products: The Project is expected to enhance cost competitiveness and increase access to more affordable products while ensuring quality as UCL achieves further economies of scale in the market.
- Supply chain into FCS and LIIDA countries: FCS and LIIDA countries suffer from most critical healthcare situation in the region in particular regarding access to quality and affordable drugs. UCL's supply chains into these countries will be key in addressing these challenges. 
- Employment: The Project is expected to create direct and indirect skilled employment.<c2>&nbsp;

The Project will:
(i) offer alternative sources of long-term financing to non-bank financial institutions NBFIs which will on-lend to MSMEs;
(ii) result in an increase in competitive pressures that affect the market by improving the operating standards of NBFIs;
(iii) promote greater deepening of the local capital market through replicable instruments such as CKDs and private debt funds.

The Fund is expected to have a significant development impact by: 
(i)            Providing growth and expansion capital to SMEs invested in the Kyrgyz Republic, an IDA country;
(ii)           Value addition through capacity building in operational, marketing and financial aspects of SMEs;
(iii)          Stimulating job creation and economic growth by supporting fast-growing SMEs;
(iv)          Implementing best practice environmental, social and corporate governance standards at both the Fund and investee levels.

(i) Improve access to finance for underserved population segments in remote areas of Kazakhstan through supporting KMF's lending activities; 
(ii) Contribute to job creation and upgrading the quality of life at the base of the pyramid through strengthening the microfinance sector in frontier regions of Kazakhstan;
(iii) Create a demonstration effect in following best practices in Kazakhstan's microfinance industry through helping KMF upgrade its risk management practices and prepare for transformation into a bank.

Increase Access to Finance in China: the proposed investment is expected to increase access to finance for vocational education students who lack of long working experience or existing wealth/properties and therefore have limited access to bank loans, and also help them establish credit records;
Promote Big Data-based Credit Assessment Methodology: the proposed investment is also expected to promote the usage of big data based lending methodology, which can help improve the efficiency and coverage of financing;
Increase Access to Education in China: the proposed investment is expected to enable more young people in China, who has vocational education needs, but has limited financial capacity to pay tuition at once, to access quality vocational education; and
Improve the Employability and Productivity for Young People: through participating the vocational educations, the students can equip themselves with knowledge and skillset urgently needed for employment or productivity improvement.

The Fund is expected to have a significant development impact by: 
(i)	Providing growth capital to SMEs invested in FCS countries;
(ii)	Value addition through capacity building in operational, marketing and financial aspects of SMEs;
(iii)	Stimulating job creation and economic growth by supporting fast-growing SMEs;
(iv)	Implementing best practice environmental, social and corporate governance standards at both the Fund and investee levels.

1. Stakeholder Impact: 
Access to affordable / mid-income housing for customers in the Low-Income State (LIS) of Rajasthan and in Tier II cities in India;
Access to senior living houses for senior citizens
Project to provide 5,000-6,000 units over the next 5-7 years; development of 200 to 250 units for the Economically Weaker Section (EWS) and lower Low Income Group (LIG) segments in the LIS of Rajasthan.

2. Value-added and employment impact:
Creation of ~1,800 jobs direct jobs through the Project, a large number of which are expected in the LIS of Rajasthan; jobs will be created in construction, marketing, and sales amongst other verticals;
Creation of a number of indirect jobs through supply linkages.

3. Environment Impact and Sustainability: 
All projects will be executed under the IFC Excellence in Design for Greater Efficiencies (EDGE) or Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) certification; 100% of the Project will contribute towards climate change. 

4. Competitiveness: Lean operations across verticals to provide demonstration effect to the market;

5. Inclusiveness: Project to develop 5,000-6,000 units in the underserved affordable / mid-income housing segment;

- Stakeholders' impacts: i) benefits to soybean and sunflower farmers who will secure a reliable access to market, and ii) benefits to the end consumers who benefit from improved food security as a result of larger volumes of oilseeds (+900,000 metric tons) and their derivatives brought to market;
- Support the Competitiveness of an Export-Oriented Sector in Argentina: as Argentina slowly reengages with the global capital markets, IFC's support to Vicentin should send positive signal to other investors about the strong prospects and solid fundaments of the oilseeds sector in Argentina, which is globally competitive and relevant in the international markets;
- Environmental and Social Standards: IFC investment is expected to further enhance Vicentin's E&S performance in a number of areas by setting performance indicators and targets.

(i) Expand financial access to the most underserved agricultural MSMEs;
(ii) Promote big data based agri-lending: through introducing the advanced internet and mobile based financial services to agricultural MSMEs, and accumulating the necessary data for framers and MSMEs along the supply chain, the proposed business model could potentially bring revolutionary change to the traditional rural finance service approach and lay a solid ground for the future big data based agri-lending;
(iii) Serve as a pilot program and catalyst to encourage other FIs and ecommerce companies to explore the feasible service model for China rural market.

(i)	Support job creation: The Fund is targeting mid-cap companies, key drivers of emerging market job creation; 
(ii)	Access to finance: improving access to long-term equity capital for SME and mid-market companies in North and West Africa; 
(iii)	Corporate Governance & ESG: MCP has proven record of improving corporate governance and ESG of investee companies through hands-on approach and operational support.

This Project is expected to have high development impact with significant social and economic benefits:
(i) supporting one of the leading private banks in the market by investing in the bank's first mortgage covered bond issued in local currency;
(ii) improving access to housing finance to Turkey's young and fast growing population, where market penetration remains quite low with a residential mortgage loan-to-GDP ratio of 7.3 percent as of year-end 2015;
(iii) increasing the share of green mortgages in the market; and
(iv) continuing to help develop Turkey's capital markets through the issuance of a new instrument<e2>?'the country's first mortgage covered bond issuance in local currency.

1) Increase in processing activity and value addition across the value chain: Consumer product companies in emerging markets are contributing to development across the value chain, by modernizing manufacturing and logistics services through increased processing activities;
2) Large-scale employment: The Company, on a combined basis, employs approximately 600 full-time employees and, with the projected organic growth, the Company will be substantially increasing this number by 2021;
3) Highly diversified reach: outside of the Company's core markets, the Company reaches to markets including Democratic Republic of Congo, Djibouti, DRC, Ethiopia, Gabon, Gambia, Liberia, Mali and Somalia, among others.  The Company intends to disseminate high quality food products at affordable prices to these states;
4) GBfoods' innovative pipeline of convenience products adds value to the African consumer by saving both money and cooking time versus the alternative of buying individual ingredients;
5) Promoting South / South investment: the proposed integration of brands and assets will form a unique business that encourages other local and multinational FMCG players to pursue investment opportunities across Sub-Saharan Africa;
6) Local farmers' linkage: the long-term backward integration plan is anticipated to reach local farmers across its supply chain.

The Project is expected to:

-   generate around 607GWh of clean, zero emissions electricity per annum, serving approximately 125,000 individual households; 
-	avoid greenhouse gas emissions ("GHG") of approximately 390,000 tons of CO2 per annum 
-   diversify Jordan's fuel mix and improve energy security by generating electricity from a domestic resource;
-	help lower NEPCO's average generation costs (average of US12 cents/KWh in 2015) and contribute towards an improvement in NEPCO's financial position; and
-   help Jordan meet an increasing demand for electricity, in part driven by the growing influx of refugees in the country.

-	Infrastructure development: LLP will help address the existing shortages of quality industrial and logistics property infrastructure in Lima, where there is no supply of efficient, Class-A buildings to service multinationals and local equivalents; 
-	Business efficiencies and linkages: The modern, high-quality infrastructure developed by LLP will result in improved efficiencies and reduced operational costs for local businesses and supply chains. Class A developments can be significantly more efficient with lower operating costs than existing properties in these markets, given some of their characteristics. These include: higher ceilings, increased floor load capacity, column-free span areas, intensive docking ports with levelers for all types of trucks, and ample maneuvering yards for large vehicles. LLP estimates that in Lima the improved cost efficiency of its properties with respect to those of its competitors is at least 100% vs Class C properties and between 30% to 40% for the best Class B properties; 
-	Economic growth, job creation and supply chain development: The Project will drive the creation of direct jobs during both construction and operations, also supporting a significant number of indirect jobs through the supply chains of its tenants. The sourcing of construction inputs and related services during the subsequent development phases will foster the development of local SMEs and support local suppliers; and
-	Improved standards: LLP is also strengthening its ESG practices contributing to the overall improvement of quality standards in Peru, including E&S and life and fire safety standards as well as in terms of building construction methods and energy efficiency features.

1. Support the development of the SA automotive industry; 
2. Introduce new products and processes, and increase the competitiveness of the SA automotive sector; 
3. Maintain/sustain direct employment and generate indirect employment opportunities;
4. Support the local economy through export diversification;
5. Support the development of local suppliers; 
6. Increased local value added.

- Act as a catalyst for the professionalization of the private hospital sector in Brazil, through the implementation of Rede Dor's best practices in medical, E&S and corporate governance standards into the newly acquired hospitals;
- Expand access to high quality medical care, as demand for high-quality tertiary care is increasing in Brazil, and international standards of care are still limited and insufficient throughout the country;
- Enhance  cost competitiveness by supporting a scalable business model in a very fragmented and inefficient sector;
- Potential for a climate friendly IFC investment, through the implementation of greenbuilding standards in the new greenfield facilities;
- Employment of local professionals, most of them women (75% of the Company's workforce);
- Address Brazil's important skill gap issue by providing adequate training to the workforce through Instituto D'Or (IDOR). IDOR is also initiating an undergraduate education program and has also initiatives in specialization programs and partnerships with several national and international universities;
- Support Zika-related research undertaken by IDOR with results getting international exposure and similar research being extended into the future;
- Improve the quality of the public healthcare system, as Rede D'Or has a partnership with the Rio de Janeiro State Government to manage a 80-bed pediatric hospital that has an average of 17 daily procedures, ranging from medium to high complexity surgeries such as transplants and cancer treatment.

(i) To help address the increasing need for life and health insurance products and non-family support for elder care during the trend of aging population in China;
(ii) To support the improvement of the social safety net in China through the development of commercial insurance as alternative protection mechanism;
(iii) To contribute to transforming domestic savings into long term risk capital by helping the Company strengthen its investment function;
(iv) To help build a model life insurerance company through board participation, corporate governance advisory, risk management advisory and knowledge sharing, and therefore to support the development of China's life insurance sector

(i) MS Pharma's strong product pipeline and R&D capability will increase the availability of a wide range of quality medicines in the MENA region;
(ii) The Project will reduce reliance on imported medicines and expand local pharmaceutical manufacturing capacity;
(iii) The Project will generate direct employment opportunities for skilled labor in MENA; and
(iv) The investment will support south to south expansion.

a) Increase availability of quality drugs in Turkey and Central Asia as Nobel will expand its products portfolio and venture into bio-tech drugs and injectables.
b) Increase exports and import substitution as Nobel will expand its products portfolio outside of Turkey which will contribute to reducing the country's pharmaceutical trade deficit. In addition, the bio-tech products that will be produced by Nobel will be local substitutes for imported drugs, which the Turkish government is keen on promoting;
c) Increased R&D activities in Turkey, which will support the government's agenda to boost local R&D and production and reduce the pharmaceutical trade deficit;
d) Generate direct employment opportunities for skilled labor in Turkey.

i.	Stimulate access to financing to individuals, micro and small enterprises as a key contributor to country's economy;
ii.	Create job opportunities for entrepreneurs and individuals in the rural area, including women, with direct impact to poverty reduction;
iii.	Serve as demonstration effect to other MFIs in introducing best practices in insurance, environment and social systems.

This project is expected to:
(i) Add base load capacity to Senegal's interconnected system helping the country meet it's fast growing electricity demand, and therefore stimulate further economic growth;
(ii) Add flexibility in handling electricity demand and improve the system's overall stability and reliability given its convenient location on the network;
(iii) Displace some of the more expensive energy sources (i.e., rental emergency power plants and older less efficient thermal plants), and hence improve Senelec's financial situation;
(iv) Provide flexibility and cleaner energy to the system as the engines are converted to gas, as this become available in the future; and 
(v) Support Senelec's efforts to establish a strong track record of private sector participation, as it seeks to attract new investors to the country's power sector.

The project's development impact is the following:
(i) Through the injection of new capital, strategic direction, and IFC's support, Orazul Energia will develop and potentially invest in new opportunities in renewable energy - organically or through further acquisitions;
(ii) By providing base load capacity and energy grid reliability, the project will support the diversification of the different country's energy matrix and enable the environment for the increased penetration of intermittent renewable energy technologies, such as wind and solar; 
(iii) Increase private participation in Latin America's energy sector; 
(iv) Supports the diversification of the pool of investors in the Latin America energy sector which increases competition, preserves employment and supports regional integration; 
(v) IFC signals to the market of its support towards the recent government reforms in the energy sector in Argentina.

The Project will:
(i) help add new generation capacity in Jordan and generate over 145 GWh (at P50), meeting the growing demand for electricity in Jordan, serving approximately 83,000 customers annually based on a per capita consumption of 2,100 kWh; 
(ii) diversify the fuel mix for Jordan and provide for energy security by generating electricity from a domestic resource; 
(iii) displace thermal power that has a average cost of ~ 50% above the tariff helping to alleviate the losses borne by NEPCO; 
(iv) avoid greenhouse gas emissions (GHG) of approximately 110,000 tons of CO2 per annum.

- Increased access to quality and affordable healthcare services, especially in underserved regions of Georgia: Georgian consumers will benefit from having access to an extended network of health centers with high quality medical services at affordable prices.
- Employment generation and preservation: The Company is one of the largest employers in the country with around 6,700 full time employees, around 70% of which are women. 
-Increased tax payments: Generating additional amount of taxes to be paid to the State;

The Project is expected to have the following development impacts:
(i) South-south investment by Acibadem, a leading private healthcare network in Turkey will bring in operational knowhow and capital to the private healthcare sector in Bulgaria;
(ii) Consolidation of private healthcare providers in Bulgaria with strong management is expected to unlock synergies and economies of scale bringing down costs and increasing of access to healthcare due to higher efficiency;
(iii) The Project is expected to increase access to specialized services (oncology and cardiology) funded by the social health insurance but at a limited supply from public sector providers;
(iv) Demonstration effect of creating the largest integrated private health network in Bulgaria will facilitate private sector investment in private healthcare providers in the country and in the region.

IFC's investment will make Mexican electronic factoring market more competitive, contributing to more efficient transactions, cost reduction, and better use of working capital for participating SMEs in the supply chain.  SMEs will benefit by:
	a) improving financial liquidity for their operations and improved working capital; 
	b) increased certainty of payments; 
	c) lower financing costs by getting access to a larger set of financial institutions; 
	d) multiplier effect, in which SMEs can also improve the financial liquidity of their own supply chain.

(i) Raise quality standards:  Strengthening Estacio's position as a leading education company in Brazil will potentially serve as a catalyst for other leading education institutions to continue to raise the quality of their services;
(ii) Improve access to services:  Estacio's plans to expand its network, particularly in Southeast and frontier regions such as the Brazilian North and Northeast, will enhance the country's education infrastructure and improve access to quality, affordable education services for lower income students;
(iii) Rationalize the market: Through its organic growth and planned acquisitions, Estacio will continue to rationalize the still fragmented education sector and increase efficiencies in acquired companies; and
(iv) Expand reach of community service activities: Estacio's expansion in number of enrolled students and into new geographies will allow the Company to provide services to many additional people and a greater range of communities ( services may include legal advice, income tax filling advice, dental, medical and physiotherapy care, waste management and recycling studies and services at price below the market prices, by both students and faculty).

The Fund will have a high development impact, which includes but is not limited to:
(i) Reduction of GHGs; 
(ii) Adoption of more environmentally sustainable practices;
(iii) Improvement in clean energy technology in China;
(iv) Job creation including in the frontier regions; 
(v) Demonstration effect by strengthening investee companies and making them targets for acquisition and investments;
(vi) Privatization of renewable energy assets developed by SOEs; and
(vii) Developing and financing renewable energy projects in the frontier regions of China.

The project will create significant benefits to the communities where Ecom operates in terms of employment, business opportunities for small farmers and promotion of sustainable business practices. IFC quasi equity financing and the Advisory Services programs will, directly and indirectly, enable Ecom to expand its sustainability programs which will generate the following development impacts:
-	Improved E&S practices at the farm level and improved traceability and certification of cocoa and coffee;
-	Demonstration effect: other physical merchants attracted to Better Cotton Initiative;
-	Increased farmers' income through training, improved access to market and improved farm productivity. 
-	Improved access to finance for farmers and ability to implement capex at the farm level with-multi-year payback periods where Ecom extends supplier advances

IFC's participation in AM is expected to:

(i) Continue to increase availability of general insurance products in Chile, particularly in the areas of life and agribusiness insurance;

(ii) Support Chilean small and medium enterprises through the provision of competitive credit insurance through the recently created "garantia y credito" operations, which is targeted towards underserved Chilean SMEs.

- Increase access to quality healthcare services in Romania, including in cities outside Bucharest;
- Relieve burden on over-crowded public system and support a viable private sector alternative which is increasingly seen as necessary to address healthcare needs in the country;
- Continue to establish benchmarks for quality healthcare, in preventive and specialized care in line with market demand;
- Promote transparent practices in the local health sector and raise standards of quality and ethics;
- Offer employment and development opportunities for health personnel in an environment conducive to the practice of high quality medicine.

The development impact of this project includes: 
(i) housing supply - alleviate the current housing shortage in Mexico; 
ii) community development - development of states and municipalities facilitating the efficient provision of municipal services; 
(iii) economic growth - contribution to the economic growth in the regions where investments will be made as a result of public private participation; and 
(iv) job creation - the project will create job opportunities both during construction and operation of the communities; 
(v) enhanced local supply linkages - increase demand for construction and building materials in the country.

Consumer Benefits: the expansion of the Company's retail chain in the Central and Eastern Europe, as well as in the Middle East and North Africa regions, will enable ALH Retail to provide for its customers better access to a more diverse selection of high-quality, affordable apparel. This will be especially important for consumers in such countries as Azerbaijan and Georgia where modern apparel retail sector is still nascent. Stronger bargaining positions vis-a-vis suppliers, economies of scale achieved through geographical expansion, as well as improved inventory management are expected to result in cost savings, which eventually can be passed on to the end customer; 
Employment Generation: the expansion of the Company's operations will create 1,000 permanent jobs. In addition, ALH Retail's large-scale expansion will involve numerous leasehold improvements, which will generate temporary employment;
Life and Fire Safety ('LFS') Improvements: As a condition of the IFC investment, ALH Retail will commit to implement an improved LFS Action plan;
Supporting IFC's reach in frontier regions and south-to-south investments: establishing a long term partnership with an important local player in its expansion plans to surrounding developing countries;

- The Project will enhance access to long-term finance for farmers and SMEs, enabling Itau Paraguay's clients to undertake capital investments at longer tenors and competitive terms;
- Due to the maximum average sub-loan size of up to US$1 million, the facility will be 100% used to serve SMEs;
- The mobilization of resources from other DFIs into Paraguay will support and consolidate the improvement of the business climate experienced by the Country over the past few years.

- Create market alternatives for insurance companies which today are dependent on a few available options to obtain reinsurance;
 Increase domestic reinsurance capacity;
 Development of technical expertise in reinsurance in the Brazilian markets

1. IFC's strategy includes a focus on under-served markets, such as Tripoli which is Lebanon's 2nd largest city and is based in a 'Frontier Region'. This will be IFC's first investment outside of Beirut, and will contribute to more balanced regional growth, which is essential to support greater social cohesion; 

2. Support development of high value addition in the ICT sector in Lebanon: figures released by the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development ('UNCTAD') indicate that Lebanon is one of the largest exporters of Information and Technology ('IT') services among the middle East and North Africa ('MENA') region. Supporting companies like MobiNetS help demonstrate Lebanon's ability to produce world class ICT services;

3. Increase employment opportunities through companies like MobiNetS, which benefit local ICT professionals by creating high quality job opportunities and developing skills in the value-added ICT services sector. This investment can also help these businesses retain talent within Lebanon, increasing the country's chances of further economic prosperity; and

4. Support cost effective infrastructure services:  investing in a company like MobiNetS which contributes to reduce inefficiencies and generates cost savings, is fully in line with the World Bank Group's strategy in the ICT sector.

The project is expected to have the following development impacts: 
Provision of Business Infrastructure Services: The project will add 29,383 square meters of quality real estate infrastructure to Kigali and support the implementation of the Kigali City Master Plan;
Employment: The project will create a minimum of 100 jobs during construction and further 15-20 jobs post construction. The project will also create indirect jobs through supply chains;
Demonstration Effect: IFC's involvement in the project will act as a catalyst to encourage other financial institutions to partner with strong and reputable local sponsors on similar projects in the country;
Energy Efficiency: The property design includes energy efficient components like solar powered extractor fans, heat reflective glass etc that when implemented will have a demonstration effect as one of the few true energy efficient buildings in Kigali.

IFC's expected development impact from a potential investment in Microvast includes: 

Helping China address climate change challenges by financing a company that manufactures energy and cost efficient battery technology;

The success of this Project is expected to accelerate the development of the electric vehicle industry in China. The Project will also assist the government of China to promote the replacement of buses powered by traditional fuel with hybrid or electric buses, thus decreasing the overall carbon emissions and improving cost efficiency over time;

Replacing thousands of buses running on traditional fuel per year with electric batteries could save up to millions of kilograms of CO2; and

Enabling product transfer to other developing regions, such as Southeast and Central Asia

1.	Increase access to finance to small and middle enterprises in Mongolia;
2.	Create jobs and improve livelihood as a result of supporting access to finance; and
3.	Support the Mongolia banking sector by strengthening the capital position of the largest bank in the country.

IFC development impact in Euroleasing investment will be measured according to the following indicators:

i) increased reach an improved access to leasing services for SME's and agricultural clients;
ii) introduction of innovative leasing products for agri-clients; 
iii) support a leading independent player through an equity investment and long-term funding.

i) Increase access to specialized technical vocational education & training (TVET) or higher education for lower to middle income students in regions not well served by post-secondary education and in fields closely linked to employment needs in Philippines and globally; 
(ii) Employment generation in the six project locations;
(iii) Immediate employment opportunities for graduates; and
(iv) Opportunity for students and workers to continuously upgrade skills

- The Project will allow Banco Regional to provide its SME clients access to funding with longer maturities enabling them to undertake capital investments at longer tenors and attractive costs;
- Given the nationwide presence of the Bank, the Project will contribute to rural economic development while reaching the BOP in rural areas;
- Due to the maximum average sub-loan size of US$1 million, the facility will be 100% used to finance SMEs;
- IFC will enhance its support to the expansion of a leading financial institution in the Paraguayan system.

The Project is expected to have high economic and developmental impact, as it will:

- Provide a valuable positive signal to international lenders and investors as Pakistan plans to build ~10,000 MW of capacity between 2010 and 2015, most of which developed on an IPP basis;

- Provide a much needed capacity as the installed capacity in Pakistan fails to keep up with the rapid growth of peak demand (~7% p.a.), as a result, economic actors are expressing concerns over supply deficit and load shedding measures, which are likely to continue for some time;

- Contribute to reduce greenhouse gas emissions;

- Create a sustained economic activity by providing job opportunities and an adequate road infrastructure thus improving life conditions of neighboring rural populations;

- Reduce the fuel oil import burden by using a domestic source of energy which is a relief for the country's balance of trade.

The project is expected to achieve a strong development impact through promoting and enabling growth of the financial services sector in Vietnam. This should include the following:
Return on Equity;
Increasing access to finance for SMEs;
Increase in Energy Efficiency (EE) and Clean Production (CP) portfolio;
GHG emission reduction.

The investment will support the growth of a competitive tomato producer in Mexico through: 
(i)	Cost reduction through higher utilization of capacity and economies of scale; 
